WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:07.760
Spanning the entire width of the African continent&nbsp;
from Senegal to Eritrea by the Red Sea, the Sahel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:13.040
Region forms the southern transition zone from&nbsp;
the Great Desert, the Sahara, to the Sudanian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:20.080
Savannah. Dominated by shrubs and grasses, the&nbsp;
Sahel is generally hot and barren, and typically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:25.360
not considered particularly habitable. Examining&nbsp;
the area’s satellite photography however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:31.440
a few pockets of greenery defy the semi-arid&nbsp;
step with the border region between Nigeria,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:38.160
Niger, Chad and Cameroon being the most colorful&nbsp;
outlier. This harbour of life is called Lake Chad&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.600
and it tells a fascinating story about the&nbsp;
fragility and resilience of mother nature and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:49.920
gives insights into the grand planetary cycles&nbsp;
that shape the climate and life on planet earth.&nbsp;

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.360
Chapter 1) Lake Chad today
During the peak of the wet season,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.360 --> 00:01:01.520
Lake Chad covers around 18.000 square kilometers,&nbsp;
comparable to the size of Lake Ontario, when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:06.880
include the seasonally flooded vegetation&nbsp;
between the deeper bowls. With a water depth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:12.640
ranging from just a few centimeters to just 11&nbsp;
meters at its deepest sections, Lake Chad is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:19.200
extremely susceptible to size changes, whenever&nbsp;
the balance of inflow and evaporation changes.&nbsp;

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:23.440
Most of the water in Lake Chad comes&nbsp;
from the Logone and Chari Rivers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:29.280
whose furthest tributaries reach all the way from&nbsp;
Cameroon, across the Central African Republic to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:33.440
the southern most parts of Sudan. Rain in&nbsp;
the Highlands around the sources of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:38.400
tributaries is highly variable throughout the&nbsp;
year, leading to discharge variations from around&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:44.480
8 cubic meters per second during the dry season to&nbsp;
almost 5000 cubic meters per second at the peak.&nbsp;

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:50.000
These variations are shooting an annual pulse&nbsp;
into the Chad basin, making the lake expand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.760
and recede like the lungs of central Africa.
The area we call Lake Chad today is actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:00.960
split between two shallow basins that stretch&nbsp;
for over 200 kilometres from north to south.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:06.560
The core of Lake Chad is located in the south&nbsp;
where the Chari River contributes around 95%&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:12.000
of the lake's water balance, while the north has&nbsp;
the Yobe river contributing the remaining water.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.480
For most of the year, the two basins&nbsp;
act as separate wetland complexes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:22.000
which are separated by the so-called Great&nbsp;
Barrier, a mud sill lying around 1 to 1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:27.120
meter above the normal level of the southern&nbsp;
basin. Only during particularly wet seasons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:33.200
does the main lake rise enough to breach this&nbsp;
barrier, extending Lake Chad across both basins.&nbsp;

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.840
Unlike the lakes as we know them in temperate&nbsp;
climates, with a clear boundary between the wet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:43.680
and the dry, Lake Chad is more of a complex&nbsp;
wetland ecosystem than a lake. Hundreds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:49.440
kilometers of seasonally submerged grassland, and&nbsp;
extensive dunes reaching into the permanent lake&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:55.200
body create a fluid network of dry and wet,&nbsp;
where clear borders are hard to determine.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:59.680
This is one of the main reasons why there are&nbsp;
so many different figures describing the size&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:03.280
of this lake and the 18.000 square&nbsp;
meter I have used in the beginning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:08.400
of the video should be taken with caution.
With fluctuating extents of water in the basin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:14.080
the extent of vegetation is also constantly&nbsp;
bargaining with external influences.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:20.160
Mostly contained in the designated Ramsar Wetland&nbsp;
region, today around 5200 square kilometers of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:25.600
basin have permanent vegetation cover with&nbsp;
paper reed and the floating Pistia covering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:32.640
the largest swaths, while Acacia Trees and Palms&nbsp;
are more concentrated around the wetlands shores.&nbsp;

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:37.760
Where there is water, there are typically also&nbsp;
humans and for Lake Chad there is no exception.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:42.720
Looking at the lake, its surrounding wetland&nbsp;
and the vast tributary systems as a whole,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:47.280
the livelihood of a total of 30 million&nbsp;
people depends on the basin’s waters,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:53.360
of which there isn’t very much, bringing us to…
Chapter 2) Human influence on Lake Chad&nbsp;

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:59.760
Since the 1950s, the populations in all countries&nbsp;
surrounding the Chad basin have been exploding.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:07.440
The country Chad for example went from 2.5 million&nbsp;
people in 1950 to over 21 million in 2025, meaning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:15.040
an 8.5 fold increase. The extra demand for water,&nbsp;
food, fuel and land has had detrimental impacts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:20.080
on Lake Chad, which has been dramatically&nbsp;
reduced within a single human lifetime.&nbsp;

00:04:20.080 --> 00:04:26.000
When the lake was first photographed through&nbsp;
satellite imagery in 1963, it appeared as a vast,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.720
almost continuous sheet of water with dune&nbsp;
islands scattered around the eastern flanks.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:36.080
Since then however, the construction of dams in&nbsp;
the upstream regions of the Chari River and water&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:41.280
diversion for irrigation in the whole drainage&nbsp;
basin threw off the water balance significantly.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:47.520
In combination with generally reduced rainfall in&nbsp;
the 1960s and 70s, this led to a near collapse of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:53.520
the lake by the end of the 1980s. With increased&nbsp;
rainfall in the following decades, water levels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:58.640
have stabilized somewhat, but with virtually no&nbsp;
effective sustainability policies to protect the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:04.320
lake, and with irrigation and population still&nbsp;
expanding, the same threats persist to this day.&nbsp;

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:08.720
People around Lake Chad have not just tapped&nbsp;
into the water balance of the lake however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.320
but also significantly altered the land use and&nbsp;
ecological composition of the basin as a whole.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:19.760
Until the end of the 19th century, the typical&nbsp;
African Savannah megafauna was grazing and hunting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:24.880
around the shores of Lake Chad. With the advent&nbsp;
of colonialism however, intensified hunting for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:31.200
ivory, skins and meat has disrupted the natural&nbsp;
fauna. These atrocities, paired with habitat loss&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:35.600
from the growing population and the ongoing&nbsp;
droughts in the middle of the 20th century,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:41.040
led to an almost complete localized extinction&nbsp;
around Lake Chad of these animals by 1990.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:45.680
Replaced by cattle, goats and sheep, the&nbsp;
newly introduced megafauna has transformed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:52.080
a once‑diverse savannah into a more homogeneous,&nbsp;
overgrazed and erosion‑prone landscape, which in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:58.080
turn has further degraded the remaining wetlands.
Overall, human use hasn’t been too kind on Lake&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:03.920
Chad’s ecological health, but zooming out to a&nbsp;
larger timeline and the wider Bodele Depression,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:08.400
we are not the only force that drastically&nbsp;
altered Lake Chad’s appearance. Hundreds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:14.080
kilometers away from the current lake shores and&nbsp;
surrounding the deepest parts of the Chad Basin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:20.240
ancient dried out landforms emerged from satellite&nbsp;
imagery, with spits, beach ridges and fluvial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:25.600
deposits of former river deltas tracing out the&nbsp;
existence of an enormous body of of water that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:30.000
is no more, bringing us to
Chapter 3) The Mega-Chad&nbsp;

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:35.040
The very first hints that the Sahara and Sahel&nbsp;
zone may not always have looked like they do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:40.720
today, came from early explorers in the late&nbsp;
19th century. A group of British explorers in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:45.600
the southern mountains of Libya and Algeria&nbsp;
came across cave paintings, whose depictions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:51.600
went against everything we thought we knew. Vivid&nbsp;
imagery of lush savannah and herding animals were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:56.720
galloping across the cave walls, which today&nbsp;
is a sight that can’t be found for thousands&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:02.000
of kilometers from these caves. The paintings&nbsp;
are dated back to roughly 10.000 years ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.960
which implies that these regions must have looked&nbsp;
completely different during that time, for early&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:12.800
humans to be familiar with these kinds of scenes.
These observations kicked off investigations into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:19.440
earth's larger climate cycles, and culminated into&nbsp;
the description of Milankovic cycles in the 1920s.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:24.720
According to the astronomer Milutin Milankovic,&nbsp;
earth’s orbit around the sun is not as constant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:30.160
as once expected and the wobbles in the orbit&nbsp;
and spin, influenced by gravitational pull from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:35.440
other planets over tens of thousands of years can&nbsp;
drastically reshape the distribution of sunlight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:42.000
on Earth’s surface and, with it, the climate.
Cycles in orbital eccentricity at 100.000 to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:49.520
400.000 years, axial tilt at 41.000 years and&nbsp;
precession at 21.000 years create a complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:54.960
but predictable pattern for global exposure to&nbsp;
the sun’s energy, and are the foundation for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:59.840
understanding the larger natural climate&nbsp;
patterns on the planet such as ice ages,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:04.880
changes to the global ocean currents and&nbsp;
the expansion and contractions of deserts.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:09.920
Backtracking the impacts of the Milankovic cycles&nbsp;
on the Sahara, reveals that this vast barren&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:15.920
desert must have cycled between humid savannah and&nbsp;
arid desert many times in earth’s history, with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:21.920
the last wet cycle ending around 5.000 years ago.
During this African Humid Period, lasting from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:26.800
around 15.000 to 5.000 years ago, several&nbsp;
large lakes and floodplains were scattered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:31.440
around today’s Sahara, with enormous river&nbsp;
networks building a network of grass,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:37.520
wet and woodlands. Of these networks and drainage&nbsp;
basins, Lake Mega-Chad was by far the largest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:43.520
spanning a total over 400.000 square kilometers,&nbsp;
over one and a half times larger than all American&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:48.320
Great Lakes combined and even surpassing&nbsp;
today’s largest lake, the Caspian Sea.&nbsp;

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:53.520
The extent of the Ancient Lake Mega-Chad can still&nbsp;
be identified on satellite imagery and topographic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:59.760
maps today, with spits, beach ridges and fluvial&nbsp;
deposits of former river deltas tracing out the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:05.040
former lake shores. Covering the entirety&nbsp;
of the Bodele Depression of today’s Chad,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:11.760
the lake had a maximum depth of 180 meters in its&nbsp;
northeastern section. In these deeper waters, the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:17.120
fresh and brackish waters housed an abundance of&nbsp;
aquatic life, with the single celled algae called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:22.960
diatoms forming the base of the food web. The&nbsp;
ample sunlight in the region has produced billions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:28.080
of tons of these microalgae, who after their&nbsp;
roughly 1 week lifespan sink to the seafloor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:33.600
creating a thick layer of nutrient rich sediments&nbsp;
across the whole basin. Their silica shells and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:39.040
the minerals bound up in these ancient lake beds&nbsp;
form the raw material for one of the most peculiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:44.960
global connections that I have come across.
After the waters of Lake Mega-Chad have receded,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:50.000
the now hardened silica-rich sediments are&nbsp;
exposed in the Bodele Depression.There,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:55.520
a unique alignment of mountains with the Tibesti&nbsp;
and Ennedi massifs on either side, forms a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:01.520
natural wind tunnel that continuously funnels&nbsp;
strong gusts through, scouring the surface.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:06.880
The brittle sediment layers are then easily&nbsp;
eroded and made airborne as dust particles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:12.400
creating gigantic pillars of dust over the basin.
These clouds are then picked up by the prevailing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:16.480
trade winds along the equator, carried&nbsp;
over the entirety of the Atlantic ocean,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:21.920
to eventually rain down and fertiles the Amazon&nbsp;
Basin, fueling and replenishing the nutrient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:28.400
balance of the largest rainforest of the planet.
The Bodele depression is the largest dust source&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:33.360
on the planet, and it is estimated that 20&nbsp;
to 30 million tons of dust are arriving on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:38.080
the other side of the planet each year,&nbsp;
creating new life out of the remnants of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:43.600
Africa’s now decimated green and blue heart.
On the other side of the equator however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:48.720
enormous tectonic forces have created new&nbsp;
basins with an abundance of life lurking within,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:54.280
called the African Great lakes. If you want to&nbsp;
learn more how these habitats are withstanding the ever&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:59.280
changing circumstances of the African Continent,&nbsp;
I can recommend this video about Lake Malawi,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:03.520
or watch what YouTube thinks is best for you&nbsp;
here. Also, if you want to further support&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:07.040
the work I am doing on this channel, you&nbsp;
can now leave a small donation on my buy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:13.920
me a coffee page here, or with the link in the&nbsp;
description. See you in the next one, cheers.

